{
  "text": "The human sodium-glucose cotransporter family (SLC5) has 12 human genes expressed in various tissues. The corresponding membrane proteins mainly function as tightly coupled plasma membrane Na(+)/substrate cotransporters for solutes, such as glucose, myoinositol, and anions (including short-chain fatty acids); however, the family includes a Na(+)/Cl(\u2212)/choline cotransporter and a glucose activated ion channel. SGLT1 and SGLT2 (SLC5A1 and A2) have a prominent role in glucose uptake through the plasma membrane. The members of the family mediate a secondary active transport by using the sodium concentration gradient between the two sides of the membrane. They are symporters; the stoichiometric ratios of sodium coupling of SGLT1 and SGLT2 have been characterized to be 2:1 and 1:1, respectively. They can facilitate glucose uptake even against a concentration gradient; therefore, they are present in locations where glucose absorption or reabsorption occurs; SGLT1 is primarily expressed in the intestine, while SGLT2 in the kidney [CITATION_1] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "28935729"
